[normal]Q138 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] We want to start off by looking at one particular example of a situation which developed where there were some difficulties about the use of state aid. Andrew, 
[normal]I wonder whether you could
[normal] tell us a little bit about your organisation and the experience you have had to date with trying to obtain state aid, which I understand has not gone quite as smoothly as you might have hoped.
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: Our group is attempting to purchase a parcel of land or forest t
[normal]hat the Forestry Commission 
[normal]deemed surplus. We started that process five years ago. At that point in time there was no Scottish Land Fund
[normal],
[normal] but we were encouraged to attempt to do something on the basis that legislation and policy may change.
[normal]              
[normal]About two years ago—
[normal]I lose track of time
[normal]—we
[normal] had been trying different activities. The Scottish Land Fund was relaunched
[normal],
[normal] and we had a meeting with a member of staff from Highlan
[normal]ds and
[normal] Islands Enterprise, which was very encouraging. I cannot hold the guy to it—it is not his fault—but he suggested that we could get a large sum of money, in the region of potentially 
[normal]£500,000, which was a big sum in
[normal] the £700,000 purchase price
[normal],
[normal] and that we should make an application. It was very good.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q139 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Which organisation gave you that impression?
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: A guy from Highlands and
[normal] Islands Enterprise. Unfortunately what then happened, and I do not know how, is that about two weeks later or shortly afterwards—this is about two years ago now
[normal]—we were informed by Highlands and
[normal] Islands Enterprise that there could be some issues or problems with the allocation of funds from the Scottish Land Fund for the purchase of forestry by community groups. This related to application of the Eur
[normal]opean Union state aid regulations. When we went in for a meeting it was made clear to us that the state aid regulations were being applied such that the maximum grant could be 20% of the value of the forest
[normal], or €200,000, whatever that equivalent may be.
[normal]              
[normal]At that time we were attempting to buy a £700,000 forest
[normal],
[normal] and the grant that we might have been able to obtain was nowhere near enough to get us toward that £700,000 figure. In the last two years
[normal],
[normal] we have ha
[normal]d to spend more time identifying other potential ways of taking control of the forest. The biggest
[normal] problem was the 
[normal]sudden
[normal]—to us—apparent 
[normal]application of state aid regulations to the Scottish Land Fund.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q140 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you very much for that, Mr Leaver. Can we be clear to start
[normal] with
[normal]? T
[normal]he £700,000 
[normal]is 
[normal]the full open market valuation
[normal].
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: Yes. It is a valuation undertaken by the district valuer.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q141 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] T
[normal]here was no question of a discount on the price; this was purely to enable you to fund the purchase at market pric
[normal]e.
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: It was actually £690,000, to be fair. It was provided by the district valuation service in 
[normal]Inverness
[normal] as the full market value.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q142 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] I thought that was the case. I just wanted to get that clear
[normal],
[normal] because there has been some co
[normal]nfusion. When 
[normal]Highlands and
[normal] Islands
[normal] Enterprise later produced this
[normal] European rule of 20% or €200,000, apart from the inevitable heart attack, shock and all that 
[normal]side of it, what did you do
[normal]? Did you seek further clarification on that
[normal],
[normal] or did you go for any other interpretation of the rules?
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: We do not have th
[normal]e right to appeal. There is nowhere we can go
[normal] for alternative interpretation. I did write to the person here next to me, Rachael McCormack, asking for further information or some explanation. I probably wrote a letter saying, “I can’t believe this. It is an unbelievable occurrence.” Being a community member, you do that. I got a very bald answer just saying, “These are the rules; live with them.” At least that was my interpretation of the letter. We have no other recourse.
[normal]              
[normal]What was more promising perhaps—I lose track of time but it was probably summe
[normal]r 2011, so maybe 18 months ago—wa
[normal]s that there was talk of trying to get some kind of block exemption for forestry. Different Highlands
[normal] and
[normal] Islands Enterprise staff talked about ideas that they were having and approaches they would make to try and improve things. There were some very good conversations
[normal],
[normal] but that has led nowhere over this period. We have seen no progress in trying to overcome this interpretation of the state aid rules.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q143 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] Tell us about your plans for the forestry. Were you going to operate it in any commercial way? Would there be any form of trading involved? What were your plans?
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: There is a story too. When we laun
[normal]ched our campaign—let’s call it—ou
[normal]r attempt to buy the forest in 2009 
[normal]we were supported by Highlands and
[normal] Islands Enterprise. We were told that we needed 
[normal]to be a social enterprise; 
[normal]we needed to be an organisation that was run by the community, which was commercially viable and wh
[normal]ich would generate income that 
[normal]could be reinvested in the community. We pu
[normal]t together a business plan that
[normal] was about making money and reinvestment. 
[normal]Of course t
[normal]hat made us commercial
[normal],
[normal] and therefore you have to apply the state aid regulations. That was a problem for us.
[normal]              
[normal]In one of the conversations we had with HIE
[normal],
[normal] it was 
[normal]actually suggested to us that if communities were aiming to buy the land for social and environmental reas
[normal]ons and not economic ones, 
[normal]maybe they would not have to apply the state aid rules
[normal]—maybe
[normal]. 
[normal]But t
[normal]hat was a complete reversal of the advice we had received three years previously, which was to be a social enterprise and to make money. We were getting contradictory information. I have to say that that one conversation never went anywhere, so I don’t think much of it. To us
[normal] as
[normal] a community group
[normal],
[normal] it was a sign of the confusion that was going on within Highlands 
[normal]and
[normal] Islands Enterprise at that time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q144 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] 
[normal]Just for clarity, b
[normal]efore moving on to the wider issue, I asked you the question about open market value
[normal],
[normal] but if you had been able to persuade the Forestry Commission to s
[normal]ell it to you for less than 
[normal]market value, that too would have fallen foul of state aid, or didn’t this arise?
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: That did not arise. 
[normal]My understanding of the Forestry Commission is another issue, but t
[normal]he phrase
[normal] the
[normal]y 
[normal]used 
[normal]was “protecting the taxpayers’ interest” and “getting best value for the taxpayer”, which is about the open market value. I have a whole rake of things to say about how the open market value is come to, but we will save that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q145 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] I am 
[normal]about to open that up for you, because my next question is
[normal] from your evidence
[normal]. You say
[normal] that if the public benefits that could come from community ownership were i
[normal]ncorporated in the process, 
[normal]the market value might be lower. I think that is what you are suggesting. Basically that is an open question to answer as you wish.
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: There are two things. 
[normal]On the open market value for forestry, 
[normal]I have evidence
[normal],
[normal] should 
[normal]I want
[normal] to read it out
[normal],
[normal] from the DV
[normal], who
[normal] clearly states in our valuation, and in valuations for other forests which I h
[normal]ave received, that the value placed on
[normal] forestry 
[normal]does not relate to the economic returns that can be gained from harvesting the woodland. It is about the value that is placed on it because of the tax benefits to a pr
[normal]ivate owner, and a
[normal]lso sometimes—not with our particular fo
[normal]rest but in other areas of the h
[normal]ighlands—because of the person
[normal]al satisfaction and kudos of
[normal] owning a piece of land on the west coast of Scotland
[normal]. T
[normal]his adds a much inflated market value. 
[normal]              
[normal]Community groups do not have the same interest in owning a piece of land for vanity reasons
[normal],
[normal] and certainly do not have the same tax benefits in terms of inheritance and capital gains tax. The inflated value that the market puts on it is a problem for us. It is created by the tax regime that surrounds forestry.
[normal]              
[normal]Going back to your point about a reduced price from the Forestry Commission, it is something we would be very interested in talking to them about, but their interpretation of protecting the taxpayers’ interest and in the public interest purely comes down to how much money they can take back into the coffers. They interpret the Treasury rules such that there ha
[normal]s to be a financial benefit—
[normal]a financial value. Although we are talking about providing social and environmental benefits, they do not come into any calculation in relation to the public interest by the Forestry Commission when they are looking at the value of the land. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q146 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I do not know if you are familiar with it, but that is a bit like the Crown Estate’s response
[normal] to these sorts of issues. I see all the members of the panel nodding, but unfortunatel
[normal]y that does not get recorded,
[normal] therefore you have to say something.
[normal]Andrew Leaver[bold]: I am aware of the Crown Estate’s response, but not in detail.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q147 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] 
[normal]With your permission Chairman, I would like to take in some of the other witnesses. 
[normal]I would like to turn to Rachael. On this issue, sticking to forestry before we move to wider issues, what made HIE change its position? Was it new rules, new interpretation of rules or individual misunderstanding of rules? What happened?
[normal]Rachael McCormack[bold]: When the Scottish Land Fund was launched in 2012
[normal],
[normal] we identified a possible maximum intervention rate of 95%, together with colleagues in the Big Lottery and the Scottish Government. When we are talking with communities, whether it is around a Scottish Land Fund application that might be coming forward or an application in relation to any other fund—indeed an application to HIE for support—we would be at pains not to stifle their ambition. It would not be for HIE at an early stage of the conversation to be talking to a community group about whether or not they ought to aspire to a maximum intervention rate.
[normal] 
[normal]We were also not sighted in those early parts of the conversation on some of the detail, which we would need to start to look at when we had a clear idea about the nature of the proposal coming forward. 
[normal]              
[normal]As all of the Committee will be aware, forestry is a primary activity under the legislation. As such
[normal],
[normal] the state aid rules that apply are pretty clear and pretty well set out. Having said that, those rules apply to commercial forestry. If an application were to come forward from a community organisation with an emphasis, for instance, on amenity, on educatio
[normal]n or
[normal] on biodivers
[normal]ity and nature conservation,
[normal] there are 
[normal]other potential
[normal] routes that we can consider.
[normal] Rather tha
[normal]n
[normal] preclude the community from being innovative and looking at what it needs and wants
[normal] to put forward to a funder, 
[normal]HIE works with community organisations across the region supporting applications to a range of different sources of funding
[normal]. I
[normal]t is not for us to direct the community in terms of its areas of focus. Therefore we would not say “go for this intervention rate or that intervention rate
[normal],
[normal]” other than to say that there is a maximum int
[normal]ervention rate available and i
[normal]t is ultimately predicated on exactly what constitutes not just the parcel of land or assets that you would like to bring forward but the nature of the activity that you intend to take forward on that asset.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q148 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] You said just now that there may be other ways forward. I think those were your precise words. 
[normal]Rachael McCormack[bold]: Depending on the nature of the activity that the applicant is intending.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q149 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] Are you therefore talking outside the Scottish Land Fund?
[normal]Rachael McCormack[bold]: No. For clarity, in t
[normal]erms of the activity—whether i
[normal]t is economically or educationally focused or biodiversity, nature conservation or general amenity focused—the state aid rules apply to the pure economic activity. It is that commercial issue that presents the challenge. When we are clear on that
[normal],
[normal] we then interpret the legislation. It is there to be interpreted
[normal],
[normal] and I have said on a number of occasions in arenas not dissimilar to this one that the regulation is there and we work jolly hard to navigate a path through that suppor
[normal]ts the level of ambition within
[normal] our communities. 
[normal]              
[normal]A similar example in terms of a large-scale commercial forestry application that came forward to HIE, initially in anticipation of a 95% interven
[normal]tion rate from the Scottish Land
[normal] Fund, was the Colintraive and Glendaruel community group looking at over 600 acres of land that they were looking to
[normal] acquire with a view to a degree of commercial activity
[normal], but actually t
[normal]he primary focus for the community organisation was around so
[normal]cial benefit. It was around 
[normal]potential woodland crofts and housing and places for local employment, perhaps
[normal] looking at low-car
[normal]bon, locally supplied wood fuel;
[normal] but i
[normal]n order to b
[normal]e able to resource that, there wa
[normal]s a commercial component tha
[normal]t they need
[normal]ed
[normal] to extract from the
[normal] asset.
[normal] 
[normal]In discussion with ourselves and my expert staff in our community assets team, they approached a private developer with a view to 
[normal]a deal that was brokered with
[normal] the private developer who took rights to the timber
[normal],
[normal] and the intervention rate from the public purse on a £1.55 million asset acquisition was very low indeed.
[normal]              
[normal]F
[normal]rom
[normal] my point of view—
[normal]perhaps this is a particular opinion—
[normal]that
[normal] demonstrates the innovation that can be brought about when we look outside the box and think a
[normal]bout best use of public moneys, how we can bring 
[normal]innovation and new opportunities and 
[normal]actually 
[normal]challenge the basis on which we come forward to the public purse from an additionality point of view. There were other avenues for that community and they will not be replicable everywhere else, I am quite sure, but it is a good exemplar of the nature of the opportunity that can derive.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q150 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] I am sure it is and I would dearly love to follow it up, but first 
