[normal]Neil Ritch[bold]: This is my seco
[normal]nd Land F
[normal]u
[normal]nd, as it were. When operating Land F
[normal]und and
[normal] L
[normal]ottery schemes
[normal],
[normal] and investing assets
[normal] as well,
[normal] we have sought to navigate that territory. While the fundamental regulation has not changed, what does change a little is the interpretation of that regulation. That is the b
[normal]usiness that we are in as grant-
[normal]makers
[normal],
[normal] and I would say that is the situation Rachael was describing. You need a certain amount of information about a project in order to try to reach a judgment. It is a really difficult balance to strike
[normal],
[normal] between
[normal], “This is really exciting and you should do it” and “There will be some bumps in the road and there may be state aid or other regulatory challenges.” 
[normal]              
[normal]What we have sought to do in every case we have dealt with is support the community to work as effectively as they can to put together the best funding package they can within whatever regulatory framew
[normal]ork affects i
[normal]t. Where there are buildings and capital projects involved there is a whole bunch of regulatory stuff we work through, through capital experts and support contracts. In relation to state aid
[normal],
[normal] we look to structure project funding as effectively as we can to work within the rules as we understand them
[normal],
[normal] based on the advice we have
[normal],
[normal] to support those communities as best we can.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q156 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] Where has this reinterpretation come from that you imply has taken place?
[normal]Neil Ritch[bold]: I do not think I would go as far as to say it is a reinterpretation. What we try and do is make some difficult judgments.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q157 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I want to be clear. If this is not a reinterpretation, why is it that things that were previously acceptable are no longer acceptable?
[normal]Neil Ritch[bold]: I do not think it is the case that things that were previously acceptable are no longer acceptable. It is the case that we have had to structure the package in slightly different ways throughout t
[normal]he life of our investment in these
[normal] things. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q158 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Jim McGovern:[bold] That is a reinterpretation.
[normal]Neil Ritch[bold]: 
[normal]I suppose w
[normal]hat I am trying to say is that we have not seen a particul
[normal]ar new set of rules that said, “D
[normal]o things differently”. We have sought to act as effectively as we can within the advice we have. 
[normal]To that extent, w
[normal]e have always been aware of the basic state aid tests
[normal],
[normal] and we apply them to the cases that we need to fund. We then need to react to what the answers to those questions tell us. Sometimes the judgments you make in relation to those questions are different because case law emerges in relation to state aid. It is not always a precise area. It is not a piece of regulation that is well designed for the kind of business we are in, in terms of supporting communities to buy land, so it does become pretty challenging to try and walk a very straight line on it.
[normal]              
[normal]Sir James Paice:[bold] [bold]Mr Dutton wants to come in.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q159 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Mr Dutton, since this is the first time you 
[normal]will have spoken,
